    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-02-21T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-02-21T13:00:00-05:00" n="1017"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1017">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890D.01/2–2145: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-02-21T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >February 21, 1945—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 22—5:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>805. Bidault says in connection with the Department’s 633, February 16, 10 p.m.,
                    that the situation from their point of view has much improved recently. The new
                    British representative in the Levant<note n="53" xml:id="d1017fn53">Mr. Shone
                        was appointed British Minister to Syria and Lebanon on December 22,
                        1944.</note> is much more “understanding”; Bidault’s recent conversations
                    with the Syrian and Lebanese representatives here and the conversations of the
                    French representatives in the Levant recently have been encouraging. He says it
                    is his intention to reach a solution which will ensure the protection of French
                    interests but will confirm the full independence of Syria and Lebanon. He said
                    that the “fly in the ointment” in regard to the “<hi rend="italic">Troupes
                        Spéciales</hi>” is the presence of 40,000 British troops in Syria “ready to
                    take over where we leave off”.</p>
                <p>Sent Department; repeated to Beirut as 3.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
